entry.title: Reland "Reland "Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API"""
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit bbef2b40c9e20a4c8ad121ddac95abe6347389f9



This reland fixes pthreadpool cfi-call check failures in XNNPACK tests,

such as [1]. The root cause is XNNPACK casts function pointer with

incorrect signature, such as `xnn_compute_igemm` [2], to pthreadpool

task function type, such as `pthreadpool_task_2d_tile_2d_t` [3]. This

reland fixes this issue by listing related pthreadpool files in the

tools/cfi/ignores.txt instead of disabling cfi-icall build config for

pthreadpool. This fix would allow pthreadpool_unittests still be checked

by `base::PostJob` for cfi enabled build.



[1]: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20CFI/25375/test-results?sortby=&groupby=

[2]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/xnnpack/src/src/operator-run.c;l=462

[3]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:third_party/pthreadpool/src/include/pthreadpool.h;l=13



Original change's description:

> Reland "Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API""

>

> This is a reland of commit 9fd417a399dfb28ace5add2fa7df714f70de5bb6

>

> The pthreadpoool library is built with "sanitizers:cfi_icall_disable"

> config that would cause pthreadpool_unittests failure on the Linux CFI

> bot, such as [1]. This reland enables the cfi-icall sanitizer flag by

> removing this config. It also fixes a pointer cast issue in

> pthreadpool_unittests.

>

> [1]: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20CFI/25348/overview

>

> Original change's description:

> > Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API"

> >

> > This is a reland of commit e29465230b2f97fc64d51395bf9353e2ab266570

> >

> > This reland fixes the build issue on win-arm64 bots, such as [1], by

> > declaring the missing arm64 intrinsics if the arm64intr.h is not

> > included correctly due to LLVM issue [2]. Once the LLVM issue is

> > resolved, this work-around should be removed.

> >

> > [1]: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8779781271284246545

> > [2]: https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/62942

> >

> > Original change's description:

> > > pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API

> > >

> > > pthreadpool is used by XNNPACK which in turns supports TFLite and WebNN

> > > to execute each neural network operator of a model by multiple threads

> > > in parallel.

> > >

> > > To avoid creating an unmanaged thread pool owned by pthreadpool

> > > implementation, this CL implements a shim of `pthreadpool_parallelize()`

> > > that maps the pthreadpool thread tasks to work items and uses Jobs API

> > > (`base::PostJob`) to schedule these work items with Chromium's

> > > `base::ThreadPool` workers.

> > >

> > > According to the test result on a multi-core device, when scheduling 4

> > > work items with `base::ThreadPool`, XNNPACK model inference performance

> > > could get ~1.9X speedup for MobileNet V2 and ~2.8X speedup for ResNet50

> > > V2 compared to single thread execution. And the test result also shows

> > > using Jobs API shim could achieve 85% and 97% performance of using

> > > pthreadpool own thread pool implementation for MobileNet V2 and ResNet50

> > > V2 respectively.

> > >

> > > This CL also enables pthreadpool_unittests with Jobs API integration on

> > > Windows and Linux bots that aligns with the `build_tflite_with_xnnpack`

> > > build flag.

> > >

entry.title: Fenced frames: Remove COOP-swap BCG smoke test
entry.content:
This CL removes the fenced frame WPT that specifically tests input

events in fenced frames that have undergone a COOP-initiated browsing

context group swap. We remove this test for two reasons:



1. https://crbug.com/1411599 ensures that COOP headers have *no*

impact on fenced frames anymore, so this test is not operating as

it was once intended

2. All navigations in fenced frames induce a browsing context group

swap, and many tests assert that input events are handled correctly

(user-activation.https.html, for example), so what this test was

trying to assert is already covered by a myriad of others.



With COOP headers now having no impact in a fenced frame, we can remove

this redundant smoke test.



R=gtanzer@chromium.org

entry.title: Add density metric for AVIF still images
entry.content:
The original Blink.DecodedImage.AvifDensity.KiBWeighted histogram was

added by Alex Deymo in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/3257406, and

removed by Moritz Firsching in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4548468 after

it expired.



In bringing back the histogram, I made the following changes:

1. Add "2" to the histogram name so we don't mix the data with the old

Blink.DecodedImage.AvifDensity.KiBWeighted data.

2. It is recorded only for 8-bit still images, not for animated images

and not for high bit depths. Note: We probably should also exclude

grayscale images and images with alpha from this histogram.

3. The code is guarded by #if BUILDFLAG(ENABLE_AV1_DECODER).

4. AVIF tests were added to bitmap_image_test.cc.

entry.title: Refactor did_perform_url_real_time_check from bool to enum
entry.content:
This bool is used for a histogram logged by BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle.

This enum is introduced because a followup CL will update that histogram

for the case where the hash-prefix real-time check is performed.



There are no functional changes intended from this CL.



A few details about this CL:

- UrlInfo within SafeBrowsingUrlCheckerImpl used to have the bool set

and then be used later on to return the value back to the consumer.

This CL removes the property from UrlInfo during the transition from

bool to enum, and requires functions to thread through the proposed

check value. This is to ensure that all paths are setting the enum

value appropriately, since it requires considering this case.

- One of the new enum values is a "skipped" case, which describes

scenarios when none of the main check types is run. The log in

BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle currently (and before this CL as well) logs

these cases as "HashBasedCheck", which seems undesirable. This will

be re-evaluated in a followup CL.

- There are two new test cases added to cover some "skipped" cases

in SafeBrowsingUrlCheckerImpl.

- WebApiHandshakeChecker has two separate OnCompleteCheck functions.

One is defined within WebApiHandshakeChecker::CheckerOnSB, while the

other is defined within WebApiHandshakeChecker. Only the CheckerOnSB

one needs the extra parameters. The WebApiHandshakeChecker therefore

has had the extra parameters removed since they were unused.

Additionally, a new function OnCompleteCheckInternal is added to

WebApiHandshakeChecker::CheckerOnSB that only has one parameter,

which OnCompleteCheck calls into. This is so that most callers can

instead call into OnCompleteCheckInternal without providing extra

unused parameters.

entry.title: [lacros] Fix lacros failing to open after a browser crash
entry.content:
Currently Lacros will fail to open in the following situation:



1. Lacros has previously crashed (HasPendingUncleanExit() will

return true).

2. Lacros launches automatically into its windowless state.

3. Instead of re-opening the browser the user opens an app (e.g.

google meet).

4. The user then attempts to open lacros via the shelf.

BrowserServiceLacros::Launch() is called by ash in response.

3. BrowserServiceLacros sees HasPendingUncleanExit() is true and

attempts to open for the last opened profiles.

This fails because BrowserLauncher sees there is already a

browser app instance open [1].

5. Lacros fails to open.



The issue was that BrowserServiceLacros was asking BrowserLauncher to

launch for last profiles - without checking whether the invocation

had completed successfully.



This CL makes BrowserLauncher::LaunchForLastOpenedProfiles() return

true/false depending on whether or not the operation succeeded in

launching Lacros.



The condition for whether LaunchForLastOpenedProfiles() can complete

successfully has also been updated. Instead of checking whether a

browser instance currently exists we instead check if the list of

last opened profiles has been clobbered during the current session.



In most cases opening a Browser instance will clobber the profile

list - but the last opened profile list will remain valid if an

App is launched instead of the browser (see crrev.com/c/2546841 ).



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/lacros/browser_launcher.cc;l=43;drc=8311c1a3c99d5fbad8781e6e1b4d4c3af3a06e6a

entry.title: Call ProcessPrng not RtlGenRandom/SystemFunction036
entry.content:
Calling RtlGenRandom causes advapi & cryptbase to load, ultimately

causing a handle to \Device\KsecDD to be opened in the renderer

that we do not need.



This CL replaces Chrome's calls to RtlGenRandom / SystemFunction036

with calls to bcryptprimitives!ProcessPrng or base:: functions.

In Windows 10 and onwards RtlGenRandom is simply a direct call to

ProcessPrng so this does not change any behavior. See doc[1] for

details.



Before this CL these functions got system randomness from calls to RtlGenRandom. This function is undocumented and unsupported,

but has always been available by linking to SystemFunction036 in

advadpi32.dll. In Windows 10 and later, this export simply forwards

to cryptbase.dll!SystemFunction036 which calls ProcessPrng()

directly.



cryptbase!SystemFunction036 decompiled:



```

BOOLEAN SystemFunction036(PVOID RandomBuffer,ULONG RandomBufferLength)

{

BOOL retval;

retval = ProcessPrng(RandomBuffer,RandomBufferLength);

return retval != 0;

}

```



In addition:



- ProcessPrng takes a size_t length argument, making

it easier to call in Chrome's wrappers.

- ProcessPrng involves loading fewer DLLs.

- Removing all calls to RtlGenRandom prevents cargo-culting it back

in where it might be used in the renderer.



Note: boringssl still uses RtlGenRandom. If UseBoringSSLForRandBytes

is enabled base/rand_util.h functions use RtlGenRandom().

boringsll will be switched to ProcessPrng in a following CL.



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/13n1t5ak0yofzcadQCF7Ew5TewSUkNfQ3n-IYodjeRYc/edit

entry.content:
This fixes a bug where print servers from policies are not applied in

managed guest sessions.

called, which does nothing if callback_ is not set by SetListener().

print server policies change.

This bug does not affect normal user sessions because user policies get

fetched and processed after login.

entry.title: Treat component failures leniently in @font-face src: parsing
entry.content:
Adapt font-face src: parsing behavior to more leniently accept a src:

line that has parse errors in an individual component. Part of Interop

2023 in the font feature detection and palettes category [1].



Also return serialized values in lowercase to match CSSOM spec.



After CSS WG resolution [1] and updated spec text [2] individually

failing src: line components for incorrect format() or tech(), or other

parse failures per component should not lead to dropping the whole src:

line, but only reject the individual component.



Implement checks for component sanity and on failure, skip to next comma

or end.



Test updates:

* fast/css/font-face-src-parsing.html updated to account for more cases

being allowed. For example, trailing commas in a src: line are not a

full parse failure.

* fast/css/font-face-unquoted-local.html removed. The test is too

restrictive after the behavior change, and relatively trivial and

already covered in WPT tests, for example

font-format-src-parsing.html.

* fast/css/fontfaceset-multiple-families.html updated to account for a

@font-face with format("svg") being rejected early and thus not

becoming part of the FontFaceSet of the page.

* external/wpt/css/css-fonts/format-specifiers-variations.html disabled

until review in https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/40666

is complete. Test seems to be expecting an incorrect error type,

NetworkError vs. SyntaxError.



[1] https://wpt.fyi/results/css/css-fonts/parsing?q=label%3Ainterop-2023-fonts

[1] https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/6340

[2] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-fonts-4/#font-face-src-parsing

entry.content:
...if kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos is enabled.

data attached to it. However, its state (enabled or not) gets plumbed

to SessionSyncService (which uses it to determine whether to expose

the OpenTabsUIDelegate, i.e. tabs from other devices), and is also

exposed in the sync protocol itself.
